  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why do VR headsets cost so much when you can buy a phone with similar features for less than quarter of the cost?",
  "response": "The cost difference between VR headsets and smartphones, despite some overlapping features, can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Specialized Technology**: VR headsets use advanced technology that is specifically designed for immersive experiences. This includes high-refresh-rate displays, low-latency sensors, and specialized lenses to provide a wide field of view and depth perception. These components can be more expensive to produce than those found in typical smartphones.\n\n2. **Tracking Systems**: Many VR headsets come with intricate tracking systems, including external sensors or built-in cameras that allow for room-scale tracking. This technology requires additional hardware and processing power to translate the user's movements into the virtual environment accurately.\n\n3. **Computational Power**: VR applications often require more computational power than typical smartphone applications to create a seamless, immersive experience. This can necessitate higher-quality GPUs and CPUs, which add to production costs.\n\n4. **Development Costs**: The development of VR platforms and content is still relatively nascent compared to mobile app development. Developers often spend significant resources to create optimized VR experiences, which can be reflected in the pricing of the hardware.\n\n5. **Market Positioning**: Sony, Oculus, HTC, and other VR companies often position their products as premium items targeting a specific market segment. This can lead to higher pricing, as they cater to enthusiasts and early adopters willing to pay for cutting-edge technology.\n\n6. **Limited Scale of Production**: While smartphone manufacturers produce millions of units, the production scale for VR headsets may be smaller. Lower production volumes can lead to higher per-unit costs.\n\n7. **Wearability and Comfort Design**: Designing comfortable headsets that can be worn for extended periods is challenging and requires ergonomic considerations and materials that can be costly to develop and manufacture.\n\n8. **Accessories and Bundles**: VR systems often come with additional accessories, including controllers, tracking devices, and sometimes even bundled software, contributing to the overall cost.\n\nIn summary, while both VR headsets and smartphones may share some features such as displays or sensors, the technology, design requirements, and market dynamics differ significantly, leading to the higher cost of VR headsets.",
